<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-864-664  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 864 664.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Nov 6 1989 v6 n44 p29(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Out of the starting gate: Alloy Computer Products Inc.,andO;Retriever/60E with Resqnet software, $795. (Hardware Review) (oneof five extended-length tape cartridge evaluations) (evaluation)andM;</TITLE><SUMMARY>Alloy Computer Products Inc's Retriever/60E extended-length tapecartridge stores 60Mbytes of data, but the company hopes toincrease capacity with compression software under development to120Mbytes.andP;  A batch file can be built automatically for unattendedoperation of the system; the company's Tiptok scheduling utilityruns the batch files required.andP;  Novell's NetWare LANs aresupported by the device, although it is not certified for 3Comnetworks.andP;  Provision of preformatted cartridges, which areavailable with the other four tape cartridges evaluated, wouldmake using the $795 system easier.andP;  The Retriever/60E pleasesusers and beta testers, who particularly like the straightforwardmenus and speed.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Alloy Computer Products Inc. (products).andO;Ticker:    ALOY.andO;Product:   Alloy Computer Products Retriever/60E (Tape drive).andO;Topic:     Tape DrivesEvaluationBack-Up SystemsCartridge Tape.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Out of the Starting GateandM;ALLOY COMPUTER PRODUCTS INC.,andM;RETRIEVER/60E WITH RESQNETandM;SOFTWARE, $795andM;Alloy's internal Retriever/60E stores 60M bytes of data, but the company isdeveloping compression software which will increase backup capacity to the120M bytes offered by other vendors, officials said.andM;On the software side, the backup-operation menu displays the files beingtransferred to disk and the status of a tape-to-disk comparison if requested.andM;As is the case with Irwin's tape software, users of Alloy's product canautomatically build a batch file for unattended operation by storing theirmenu choices in a batch file.andP;  Alloy's Tiptok scheduling utility, includedwith the base system, automatically runs the batch files.andM;Retriever/60E supports Novell Inc.andP;  NetWare LANs but is not certified to runon 3Com networks.andP;  Like Mountain Computer's product, Alloy's system protectssensitive network files by preserving NetWare trustee-rights securityinformation in a special file (TRUSTEE.$$$) on the tape for each subdirectorybacked up.andM;Alloy could make its system easier to use by offering preformattedcartridges, an option available from all the other companies mentioned here.andO;Unfortunately, users have to take on the job of formatting the cartridges --a process that can require as much as an hour for the full 60M-byte capacity.andM;Alloy Computer Products Inc. can be reached in Marlboro, Mass., at (508)481-8500.andM;----------Buyers say: Retriever does the trickandM;Buyers and beta testers alike laud the Retriever/60E extended-tape cartridge.andM;Bill Lemar, project engineer at the Sullivan Electric Co. in Cincinnati, isimpressed with its ease of use and with its price.andP;  &quot;The software is fairlystraightforward and pretty user friendly,&quot; he said.andP;  &quot;The menus are easy tofollow, and I have yet to run into a problem with it.&quot;andM;Douglas Johnston, assistant professor of landscape architecture at theUniversity of Illinois in Urbana, has been beta testing the Retriever/60E forseveral months.andP;  &quot;If the university gets another tape drive,&quot; he said, &quot;itwill be this one.&quot;andM;Johnston has been using a QIC-40 (quarter-inch cartridge) tape-backup systemfrom Irwin Magnetic Systems and said that the Retriever/60E is much faster.andM;</TEXT></DOC>